03:32.940 --> 03:37.560
we have the chance to make decisions about every aspect of how the workplace runs.

03:37.560 --> 03:40.040
So you know, what kind of work do we want to do?

03:40.040 --> 03:43.040
How do we want to make decisions?

03:43.040 --> 03:44.120
How do we deal with money?

03:44.120 --> 03:46.240
How do we find the new work?

03:46.240 --> 03:48.660
Who do we want to work with?

03:48.660 --> 03:52.200
Another member wants to work with this group, but someone else disagrees with that.

03:52.200 --> 03:53.200
How do we work this out?

03:53.200 --> 03:55.440
How do we deal with conflict?

03:55.440 --> 04:03.080
It's kind of an end-to-end workplace situation where you have the chance to, you know, be

04:03.080 --> 04:05.040
involved in every step of the process.

04:05.040 --> 04:08.400
And of course, you don't have to do that alone.

04:08.400 --> 04:10.040
You can do that with your friends.

04:10.040 --> 04:14.000
So that's the kind of model of the cooperative.

04:14.000 --> 04:25.840
Yeah, and one of the kind of, yeah, I'll come back to the website maybe in a bit.

04:25.840 --> 04:34.760
So one of the ideas behind what a cooperative is, is this listing of cooperative principles.

04:34.760 --> 04:38.160
You can see them on the right-hand side there.

04:38.160 --> 04:43.560
For example, autonomy, independence, you know, economic participation of the members, open

04:43.560 --> 04:44.880
voluntary membership.

04:44.880 --> 04:48.700
These are kind of like non-binding principles of what it means to be a co-op.

04:48.700 --> 04:52.200
Principle six, for example, that you will work with other co-ops.

04:52.200 --> 04:57.440
So you know, we want to expand cooperation in the ecosystem of groups that are trying

04:57.440 --> 05:00.640
to do this as well.

05:00.640 --> 05:09.600
And a lot of these hinge on actually having money to survive in order to practice what

05:09.600 --> 05:11.880
it means to be a cooperative.

05:11.880 --> 05:16.480
So we are a technology cooperative, and what do we do exactly?

05:16.480 --> 05:20.480
And you could kind of say we do basically everything and anything.

05:20.480 --> 05:24.280
Like we would happily develop a new piece of software, but we'd also come to your house

05:24.280 --> 05:27.080
and fix your toaster.

05:27.080 --> 05:32.120
We try to work with people that we want to work with, that we want to support, that we

05:32.120 --> 05:36.840
like their work, or that connect with our values.

05:36.840 --> 05:41.720
And one of the things we've done quite successfully, in my opinion, is to run a free software stack

05:41.720 --> 05:45.520
boat internally and for the people we work with.

05:45.520 --> 05:51.000
So we have like all the things we use, our free software.

05:51.000 --> 05:57.120
So we're pretty good at that, managing our own internal infrastructure.

05:57.120 --> 06:00.200
And so necessarily we would then just offer that to groups.

06:00.200 --> 06:02.220
Like do you want a website?

06:02.220 --> 06:04.600
Do you want your own chat system, like a matrix?

06:04.600 --> 06:06.200
Or do you want a wiki?

06:06.200 --> 06:07.600
Or do you want an xCloud or whatever?

06:07.600 --> 06:11.960
This kind of stuff, this classic hosting situation.

06:11.960 --> 06:17.080
And one of these problems that has come up, Autonautics is running like several years

06:17.080 --> 06:24.120
now, five years or so, is that it's difficult to make money when you just do hosting.

06:24.120 --> 06:28.360
People are used to just getting stuff for free, for very understandable reasons.

06:28.360 --> 06:30.600
Big tech.

06:30.600 --> 06:33.920
And at some point, we want to scale out of the code.

06:33.920 --> 06:35.200
We want to involve more people.

06:35.200 --> 06:37.200
We want to be able to make a living from it.

06:37.200 --> 06:40.840
We want to be able to survive, pay the rent, and so on.

06:40.840 --> 06:45.040
And then we started realizing that, OK, actually we're making more money, or people are happy

06:45.040 --> 06:47.640
to pay us more when we are doing support.

06:47.640 --> 06:54.320
And this is talking to people, getting on a call and being like, what is software?

06:54.320 --> 06:55.600
And then talking about it.

06:55.600 --> 06:57.000
Or what is a wiki?

06:57.000 --> 06:58.000
Everyone's saying wiki.

06:58.000 --> 07:00.360
I don't know what a wiki is.

07:00.360 --> 07:01.960
And just having a chat about it.

07:01.960 --> 07:05.200
But then also being around later.

07:05.200 --> 07:11.280
So once they ask for the thing, like an xCloud, you set it up and then you don't disappear

07:11.280 --> 07:15.400
because you're a cooperative and you intend to continue.

07:15.400 --> 07:17.520
So sustainability is one of the core principles.

07:17.520 --> 07:19.760
So we stick with them.

07:19.760 --> 07:20.760
We chat.

07:20.760 --> 07:23.680
We're contact on mail and so on.

07:23.680 --> 07:30.160
So this is kind of the dilemma of like, we want to definitely do more hosting because

07:30.160 --> 07:32.720
people need digital infrastructure to do their work.

07:32.720 --> 07:37.560
This is just like a base layer of how to organize things.

07:37.560 --> 07:39.600
But it's difficult to survive.

07:39.600 --> 07:41.960
As a technology cooperative, only doing hosting.

07:41.960 --> 07:47.280
So you need to expand what you do.

07:47.280 --> 07:54.120
And one of the places we ended up was using Cloudron, which is a kind of like one-click

07:54.120 --> 07:58.800
install open source system, which I would still recommend.

07:58.800 --> 07:59.800
It's great.

07:59.800 --> 08:00.800
It got us really far.

08:00.800 --> 08:02.840
A lot of the next slides criticize it.

08:02.840 --> 08:07.880
So I'm just going to say it's great on this slide.

08:07.880 --> 08:13.520
So you can see you have your classic selection of open source apps if you're familiar with

08:13.520 --> 08:14.520
that stuff.

08:14.520 --> 08:19.960
Like RockaChat, for example, we use RockaChat to communicate in the co-op.

08:19.960 --> 08:28.600
And what this enabled us to do was basically work with different groups that may not necessarily

08:28.600 --> 08:36.800
have money to support us, like to make it sustainable to work with them, but still support

08:36.800 --> 08:38.240
them to do their work.

08:38.240 --> 08:41.720
And Cloudron was like a really kind of like get out of jail card in that sense.

08:41.720 --> 08:46.200
It was like, okay, I can just like hit five times on this WordPress button.

08:46.200 --> 08:47.680
And we've got five WordPress sites.

08:47.680 --> 08:48.680
And people are going.

08:48.680 --> 08:49.680
They're posting.

08:49.680 --> 08:50.680
They're organizing.

08:50.680 --> 08:51.680
They're working.

08:51.680 --> 08:52.680
We're supporting them.

08:52.680 --> 08:53.680
It's brilliant.

08:53.680 --> 09:00.280
And for those that don't know, Cloudron is just like you fire up a server, you SSH into

09:00.280 --> 09:05.360
it, you run a command, it spins up this thing, and you're going.

09:05.360 --> 09:08.640
You can install multiple apps on the same server.

09:08.640 --> 09:13.280
So this really reduces the costs for rolling out digital infrastructure.

09:13.280 --> 09:18.640
Let me check time, sorry.

09:18.640 --> 09:19.640
Yes.

09:19.640 --> 09:20.640
All right.

09:20.640 --> 09:25.800
So yeah, remember I said that Cloudron is cool.

09:25.800 --> 09:34.680
But at some point, the core of the part, the front end, the web front end became proprietary.

09:34.680 --> 09:35.680
So they made a switch.

09:35.680 --> 09:39.480
In some sense, I can't blame them because, as I said, if you want to survive, you need

09:39.480 --> 09:42.800
to make a book, and you need to pay the rent and so on.

09:42.800 --> 09:45.880
But yeah, that made us nervous.

09:45.880 --> 09:50.840
When we work with people as a cooperative, we want to say we'll be around for you.

09:50.840 --> 09:51.840
We want to continue.

09:51.840 --> 09:54.560
We want to do this sustainably.

09:54.560 --> 09:59.320
And if you remember, one of the principles is like our independence.

09:59.320 --> 10:01.200
Can we exist in this world?

10:01.200 --> 10:05.920
There's, of course, interdependencies, but can we continue to do what we want to do

10:05.920 --> 10:09.960
without relying on one specific thing?

10:09.960 --> 10:15.280
So when Cloudron made the decision to make the front end proprietary, you can still use

10:15.280 --> 10:16.280
it, whatever.

10:16.280 --> 10:17.280
It's a great system.

10:17.280 --> 10:23.960
But we thought, oh no, what's going to happen?

10:23.960 --> 10:27.440
And then we started looking a bit deeper.

10:27.440 --> 10:35.920
And we realized that Cloudron, when you click and install an app, the apps are...

10:35.920 --> 10:38.320
Yeah, it's an image.

10:38.320 --> 10:40.680
So it uses a container system.

10:40.680 --> 10:43.400
It's kind of like a light virtualization layer.

10:43.400 --> 10:47.440
They're packaging all the apps themselves.

10:47.440 --> 10:52.400
So the people who work in Cloudron, Inc., or whatever, when they want to provide a new

10:52.400 --> 10:59.360
app, they say, okay, let's make a new Git repository and let's package this thing.

10:59.360 --> 11:01.540
And that's great, and it works really well.

11:01.540 --> 11:04.640
But then we realized that they had packaged...

11:04.640 --> 11:09.200
I can't remember specific apps, but take, for example, Nextcloud.

11:09.200 --> 11:12.360
They had gone, and some worker in Cloudron had packaged Nextcloud.

11:12.360 --> 11:15.920
But then we went to the upstream Nextcloud repository, and we saw they had provided an

11:15.920 --> 11:16.960
image.

11:16.960 --> 11:20.680
And then we thought, well, why aren't we just working with them?

11:20.680 --> 11:24.920
Because that would connect our values with expanding cooperation in different layers

11:24.920 --> 11:28.640
of the software stack and so on.

11:28.640 --> 11:33.160
And then the more we looked, we realized that free software communities were really converging

11:33.160 --> 11:37.920
on the idea that you have a packaged image inside your repository.

11:37.920 --> 11:41.960
So you're hacking on your source code, and you just have an image that's building.

11:41.960 --> 11:43.320
And we can use that.

11:43.320 --> 11:44.740
That's what Cloudron needs.

11:44.740 --> 11:46.560
So we were like, okay, that's interesting.

11:46.560 --> 11:49.960
Maybe let's think about that.

11:49.960 --> 12:01.320
And then the logical end of the paranoia or whatever was that we were relying on this one

12:01.320 --> 12:07.800
company, this one group.

12:07.800 --> 12:15.400
Autonomic is a cooperative that supports maybe 20-plus groups, but a large selection of them

12:15.400 --> 12:19.120
have very little money to pay for the infrastructure.

12:19.120 --> 12:23.800
So if you could imagine that Cloudron would somehow make a bigger step into more proprietary

12:23.800 --> 12:29.100
solutions or somehow increase the cost or who knows what, we'd be in a position where

12:29.100 --> 12:31.640
we can support those groups.

12:31.640 --> 12:34.680
And that's not something we wanted to deal with.

12:34.680 --> 12:41.760
So we started to try to think, like, you know, where do we make this better or whatever?

12:41.760 --> 12:44.960
And that is the start of Cloud.

