18:27.160 --> 18:33.420
and then we can specify a configuration around those images to describe how that app should

18:33.420 --> 18:40.120
look like in a deployment on a server live and well, people using it.

18:40.120 --> 18:44.960
And one of the things we noticed was that, as I said before, the configuration that was

18:44.960 --> 18:51.640
being provided by the upstream repositories was useful, but it didn't specify the full

18:51.640 --> 18:56.920
kind of end-to-end production kind of scenario.

18:56.920 --> 19:02.520
And that's kind of a big word, but for example, how to back up the app data.

19:02.520 --> 19:06.040
Like the thing is deployed, people are using it and we need to make sure their data is

19:06.040 --> 19:07.480
safe, so we need to back it up.

19:07.480 --> 19:08.480
How do we back the thing up?

19:08.480 --> 19:09.480
How do we restore it?

19:09.480 --> 19:15.360
This is kind of like a step from it works to it works and it's safe for these people

19:15.360 --> 19:16.560
to use it.

19:16.560 --> 19:23.640
And we wanted to encapsulate that into our configuration.

19:23.640 --> 19:24.640
So this is a big part of it.

